  "overviewMarkdown": "# GitHub Sub-Agent Analyzer\n\nThis plugin implements a highly cost-efficient, multi-agent RAG workflow for analyzing large GitHub repositories in TypingMind.\n\nBy leveraging Gemini Flash Lite as a \"compression agent,\" you can map out massive codebases into dense, natural language summaries. This isolates the structural signal, prevents your main model from suffering from \"lost in the middle\" attention dilution, and drastically cuts down on token costs.\n\n### Critical Cost Protection Rules:\n- **Line Limits**: Direct file retrieval (`get_full_file`) is restricted to **300 lines** (customizable) to prevent accidental context overflow.\n- **Line-Length Safeguards**: Direct file retrieval and anchor-based slicing are restricted to **1,000 characters per line** (customizable via `maxCharsPerLine`). Files containing minified code, compiled assets, or massive single-line datasets are strictly blocked to prevent expensive token blowouts.\n\n### Recommended Workflow:\n1. **Get Structure:** Fetch the full file tree to identify target code.\n2. **Analyze with Flash:** Send up to 7 files to Gemini Flash Lite to map dependencies, business logic, and generate `[SEARCH ANCHORS]`.\n3. **Fetch Code by Anchor:** Use the exact anchors to pull localized chunks of syntax (e.g., 50 lines) without relying on hallucinatory line numbers.\n4. **Get Full File:** Pull entire files securely, protected by a customizable line limit (default: 300 lines) and line-length limits to prevent accidental context overflow.\n\n*(Note: Your GitHub PAT is securely stored locally in TypingMind and passed dynamically, while your Gemini Key processes the code directly via Google's API).* \n\nOnce the diagnosis and plan are complete, you can hand the architectural directives off to an implementation agent like Google Jules.",
